    <p>Premature Optimization</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Books (As Frameworks)</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Antifragile</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Antifragility (Gains from volatility)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Payoffs thinking instead of probabilities thinking</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Level of exposure to extreme events</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Options (Short or long volatility)</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Decisive</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Search for Objective Data to Inform Decisions</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Small Experiment / Ooch</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What are the options that we’re not considering?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What beliefs do I have that I should question?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What is the evidence that contradicts my beliefs?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What are the underlying desires guiding my decision?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Assume that some or all options are eliminated or required. What do we do?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What is the opportunity cost of this decision? (Opportunity Cost)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Can we reframe between prevention focus and promotion focus?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Who else had this problem, and how can we learn from them? (History)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What evidence, if witnessed, would change your mind?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>When this went well, what was happening?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What was the close-up experience of people who made my decision in the past? (Inside View)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>How will I feel about this decision in 5 minutes, in 4 months, in 3 years?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Premortem - imagine this decision going horribly wrong and going extremely well. What caused it?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What is the courageous action? The imaginative action?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What would other people of different types do in my position? (Different person heuristic)</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Getting to Yes</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Escape Ego Association (Positional Negotiation)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Separate the people from the problem</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Escape to underlying interests, of which the positions are made</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Invent Options for Mutual Gain</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Use Objective Criteria</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>CFAR Manual</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Visualization over possible futures (similar to best state worst state)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Actually Try - OMG I need to do this all the time, it’s huge</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Murphyjitsu</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Identify motivating urges</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Identify aversive factors</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Combine objective information with Value of Information</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Inferential Distance (what knowledge is requisite)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Explain the problem in detail (to a duck)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Actually understand the problem</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Intensity</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Identify Bottleneck to problem solving</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Obvious next step that needs to happen</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Where did the problem go wrong? Did it happen earlier than expected?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Steel-Man each idea</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Mindset check - are you looking for evidence for a particular option, or genuinely a scout</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Physiology check - what’s your psychological state?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>City of Lights - separate yourself into different parts with different opinions</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>How can training occur naturally in behavior (deliberate performance)?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Overlearning - seeing an idea everywhere, immersion</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Postmortem - when this has failed in the past, what happened?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Exposure Therapy</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Fragment - break the problem into smaller pieces/chunks</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Identity - Sociology</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Poor Charlie’s Almanac</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Specialization/Comparative Advantage</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Law of Large Numbers / Poker-style optimal play, long term tends to theoretical values</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Invert! Invert the question or the situation, try reversing everything.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Mean Regression</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Backup System - All critical systems have a backup, avoid downside exposure</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Simplicity. Make as few decisions as possible, have few dependencies.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Equilibrium</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Critical Mass</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Think at the Margin</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Scarcity</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Social Proof</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Consistency</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Reciprocation</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Risk/Loss/Uncertainty Aversion</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Positive Feedback</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Catalyst</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Compound Interest</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Tight/Aggressive approach to decisions</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Pareto Principle (80/20 rule)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Man with a hammer syndrome</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Tragedy of the Commons</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>No-Brainer / Do the obvious thing</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
</ol>
